{#
  Example 01 — Default native <select>.

  The simplest possible mount. Each <option> renders with its
  locale's pretty name (from the `localeLabels` opt; falls back to
  the bare code if not provided) and its own `lang="…"` so screen
  readers pronounce each in the right language.

  Outcome: a single <select> with three <option>s. Picking one
  writes `<html lang="…" dir="…">` and fires `onChange`.

  Note the status region below the select. The closed <select> always
  reads the placeholder word, never the active locale, so a
  screen-reader user would otherwise have no way to hear which locale
  is active. The status line is part of the default pattern — see
  ../docs/accessibility.md. Omitting it is the deliberate choice.
#}
{% from "../locale-select.njk" import localeSelect %}

{{ localeSelect({
    label: "Choose your language",
    locales: ["en", "fr", "ar"],
    value: "en"
}) }}

{#
  Visible by default: it helps sighted users and cognitive
  accessibility too, and WCAG 2.2 AAA favours it. For designs that
  cannot spare the space, make it visually hidden instead of dropping
  it — recipe in ../docs/styling.md.

  aria-live="polite" announces mutations only, so this region is
  silent on first paint and speaks on each subsequent change. That is
  the intended behaviour.
#}
<p class="locale-select-status" aria-live="polite"></p>

<script type="module">
    import { autoInit, localeName } from "../locale-select.client.js";

    const status = document.querySelector(".locale-select-status");

    autoInit({
        onChange(code) {
            // localeName() resolves the human name from the built-in
            // table ("en_US" -> "English (United States)"), so the
            // region shows a real language name, not a raw code.
            status.textContent = `Active language: ${localeName(code)}`;
        },
    });
</script>
